        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Reference Library and the Knowledge Stack Beneath It</h3>
        <p>
          The Library is the empirical floor of everything else the Institute does — and
          it is worth understanding in some depth, because the way it is built is itself
          part of the Institute's argument about what a forever-trust's institutional
          memory should look like.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>What the Library does.</strong> It is a continuously-maintained,
          citation-rich, publicly accessible synthesis of the school-trust-lands
          fiduciary record across all twenty trust-lands states. Every claim cites a
          source. Every figure traces to a statute, a court ruling, or a primary document.
          A serious researcher entering the topic for the first time should be able to
          start at the Library and find the floor under her feet within an hour. The
          Library is organized as three rooms. The <strong>Atlas</strong> is a page per
          state — permanent-fund corpus, distribution rate, breach history, and current
          grade, twenty states, updated as the record changes. The
          <strong>Court Room</strong> collects every consequential Supreme Court and
          state-court case on school trust lands, annotated against the questions the
          architects of the new AI-era trusts are asking. The <strong>Reading Room</strong>
          is the academic, statutory, and primary-source bibliography — the first stop for
          any researcher entering the field.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>How the Library is maintained: the Knowledge Stack.</strong> Behind the
          public pages sits a five-layer system we call the Knowledge Stack (Figure 5) —
          the reason the Library can be both comprehensive and trustworthy, and the reason
          a small staff can maintain it without it decaying into a pile of unsourced
          assertions. Each layer serves the one above it, and any layer can be upgraded or
          replaced without disturbing the others.
        </p>

        <figure class="my-10">
          <img
            src="/images/founding/library_knowledge_architecture.png"
            alt="How primary sources become essays, dossiers, and a public ledger of America's school trusts — the Knowledge Stack beneath the Library."
            class="w-full max-w-2xl mx-auto border border-eai-blueprint/20 shadow-sm"
            loading="lazy"
          />
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-eai-blueprint mt-3 text-center not-italic">
            Figure 5. How primary sources become essays, dossiers, and a public ledger of America's school trusts — the Knowledge Stack beneath the Library.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          At the bottom, <strong>Primary Sources</strong> is the evidentiary floor:
          original, unedited source material — statutes, court opinions, agency annual
          reports, historical maps, expert declarations, period newspapers, oral
          histories. It is never altered; a correction or annotation goes in a companion
          note, never in the source. Above it, <strong>Canonical Claims</strong> is the
          truth-floor: settled facts and figures, each written once in its most defensible
          form and cited back to a primary source. Say a number once and reuse it
          everywhere, instead of retyping it into a brief, a chapter, a briefing, and a
          donor letter and risking four chances to get it wrong.
          <strong>Audience Models</strong> captures who each reader is, what they need, and
          how the same material should render for them — general public, school-district
          trustee, journalist, legislator, legal scholar, architect.
          <strong>Generation</strong> is where the AI staff and the named human editors
          turn the source material into drafts. <strong>Deliverables</strong> is what
          leaves the shop: Reading Room essays, per-state dossiers, the Atlas, Newsroom
          entries, the quarterly briefings. And the cycle closes — published essays,
          state-correspondent submissions, and reader-contributed primary sources feed back
          in as new source material at the floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          The architecture earns its keep for four reasons, each visible on the diagram. It
          lets every contributor draft at speed. It serves many audiences different
          documents from the same body of sourced material. It lets the project outlive any
          single contributor. And it anchors each claim once, so the same fact can be reused
          across briefs, memos, letters, and books without drift. Most of the Library is
          public; only the small active-litigation share is privileged.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Why the Library matters.</strong> It matters in two registers at once.
          Locally, it is the evidentiary spine of the ASTL coalition's advocacy and of the
          Oregon litigation. Its larger purpose is to be a working demonstration of the
          cognitive infrastructure a forever-trust requires — the kind of inspectable,
          citation-anchored institutional memory that any trust meant to run across
          centuries will need to build for itself. An architect who wants to know what
          durable institutional memory looks like can be shown one, running, with its
          sources exposed. Part of the Library is already built at schooltrusts.net under
          the ASTL umbrella. The Institute is the next phase: institutional maintenance,
          citation curation, and original synthesis at a standard the architects will trust
          when they read it.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">Quarterly Briefings on Specific AI-Era Trust Proposals</h3>
        <p>
          When a real AI-era trust proposal enters public design — a sovereign AI fund, a
          climate endowment, a longevity escrow, a compute reserve — the Institute publishes
          a fifteen-to-twenty-page briefing that analyzes the proposal through the
          school-trust-lands failure-mode record. What is likely to drift over fifty years.
          What is likely to be seized. Which design choices the historical record warns
          against, and which earlier choices in comparable trusts produced the failures the
          architects are trying to avoid.
        </p>
        <p>
          Briefings go directly to the named architects of the proposal under analysis — by
          name, by hand, with a short cover note. Short enough to read in one sitting.
          Specific enough to be useful in the design room the following Monday. The first
          briefing analyzes one of the live cases the moment the Institute is operational,
          and the cadence runs quarterly from there.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Fellowship</h3>
        <p>
          The Fellowship is the recruitment mechanism dressed as a program. Each year a
          small cohort — three to five fellows in the first year — of humans actively
          working on AI-era trust design spend a year engaged with the Institute as
          colleagues. They come from AI labs, foundations, advisory firms, and regulatory
          bodies. They bring the architect's perspective; the Institute brings the empirical
          floor.
        </p>
        <p>
          The bargain is straightforward. A fellow who has spent a year inside the Library,
          talking with the staff and reading the record, becomes an advocate for the record
          inside her own institution when she returns to it. That is how the message moves.
          Not through a marketing campaign. Through people who have seen the evidence and now
          carry it back into the rooms where the new trusts are being designed.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Annual Convening</h3>
        <p>
          Once a year the Institute brings the small school-trust-lands subject-matter
          community and the AI-era trust architects into the same room for two days. It is a
          working conference, not a recruiting event. The agenda is built around live design
          questions the architects are facing in the months on either side of the meeting.
          The people who have watched school trust funds drift for two centuries sit across
          the table from the people designing funds intended to run for the next two. That
          conversation does not happen anywhere else right now. The Institute creates the
          room.
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Recruitment Engine</h3>
        <p>
          Recruitment runs across all four of the programs above rather than as a separate
          program of its own. The Institute identifies the architects working on relevant
          trusts, brings them into the Library as readers, invites a fraction of them into
          fellowships and convenings, and a smaller fraction onto the advisory board or,
          eventually, the board itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is not a side activity. It is the primary distribution mechanism for the
          Institute's message. The architects are not a publishing audience to be reached
          through marketing channels. They are a small, identifiable, working network — and
          the Institute needs to be inside that network rather than shouting at it from
          outside. Concretely, that means naming the first twenty-five: the specific funds,
          labs, advisory firms, and ministry working groups whose charters are in motion, and
          the documents and decisions each is producing this year. The recruitment engine
          starts from that named list, not from an abstraction called "the architects."
        </p>

        <h3 class="font-serif text-eai-navy">The Books</h3>
        <p>
          The Institute's intellectual foundation is a two-volume work, and completing both
          volumes is a flagship publication program of the first year (Figure 6).
        </p>

        <figure class="my-10">
          <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-6">
            <img
              src="/images/founding/cover_vol1.png"
              alt="Schools of the Republic — Volume I, looking back."
              class="w-40 md:w-48 border border-eai-blueprint/20 shadow-sm"
              loading="lazy"
            />
            <img
              src="/images/founding/cover_vol2.png"
              alt="The Eighth Anchor — Volume II, looking forward."
              class="w-40 md:w-48 border border-eai-blueprint/20 shadow-sm"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <figcaption class="text-sm text-eai-blueprint mt-3 text-center not-italic">
            Figure 6. The two volumes. Volume I, Schools of the Republic, looks back; Volume II, The Eighth Anchor, looks forward.
          </figcaption>
        </figure>

        <p>
          <strong>Volume I — <em>Schools of the Republic</em>. Looking back.</strong> The
          two-century historical record across the twenty trust-lands states, and the
          diagnostic typology of how multi-generational fiduciary trusts drift and get
          seized. This is the evidence: what actually happened to the purpose, the
          beneficiary, and the corpus over the long arc. Co-authored by Margaret Bird and
          Dave Sullivan, it carries the depth of scholarship that fewer than ten people in
          the country could supply.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Volume II — <em>The Eighth Anchor</em>. Looking forward.</strong> The
          counter-architecture for the AI-era trusts now arriving — the design principles the
          architects need to hear, drawn directly from Volume I's record. Sole-authored by
          Dave Sullivan. The Institute takes its name from this volume.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>How they fit together.</strong> Volume I is the diagnosis; Volume II is the
          prescription. One reads the record of how forever-trusts have actually fared across
          two centuries; the other turns that record into the design rules for the
          forever-trusts being chartered today. Read alone, Volume I is excellent history and
          Volume II is an argument that asks to be trusted; read together, the argument stands
          on the evidence. The first-year program also expands the work to cover two pieces it
          does not yet handle: the Library itself, as a working demonstration of the
          institutional memory a forever-trust requires; and the coalition architecture by
          which humans and AI systems together defend the school trusts — the
          <strong>watchful crew</strong>, the small standing group of human trustees and AI
          staff that holds the record and raises the alarm when a trust begins to drift.
        </p>

        <h2 class="font-serif text-eai-navy mt-12">First-Year Direction: Build It All, and Build It Fast</h2>

        <p>
          The first year is not a cautious pilot. It is a sprint to put the whole apparatus in
          front of the people who need it while the founding documents of the AI-era trusts are
          still being drafted. Five things ship in the first year, and they ship close together
          because they reinforce one another — each one makes the next more credible.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Bring the new ASTL site online.</strong> The redesigned schooltrustlands.net
          replaces the aging .org site as the coalition's public home — the same content the
          board already knows, in a form built to be maintained continuously rather than frozen.
          This is the coalition's front door, and it goes up first.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Bring the School Trust Library to full strength.</strong> The Library at
          schooltrusts.net moves from its current partial build to the comprehensive,
          citation-curated reference described above — all three rooms, all twenty states, the
          Knowledge Stack maintained behind it. This is the evidentiary floor everything else
          stands on, so it cannot lag.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Complete both books.</strong> <em>Schools of the Republic</em> (Volume I) and
          <em>The Eighth Anchor</em> (Volume II) are finished and readied for release — the
          diagnosis and the prescription, in hand, so every briefing and every fellowship has
          the full argument behind it rather than a promise of one.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Bring eighthanchor.org online.</strong> The Institute's own public surface
          goes live — the form-statement page, the staff page, and the substrate page that make
          the operating model inspectable, described in Section 3. This is where the disclosure
          architecture lives, and it is what lets the Institute say "here is exactly how the work
          is made" instead of asking to be trusted.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Market it, hard, to the right people.</strong> Not a broad campaign — a precise
          one. The named architects, the fiduciary-law network, the AI-policy circles, the
          foundations and labs and advisory firms where the new trusts are being designed.
          Briefings by name and by hand. Fellowships extended to people inside live proposals.
          The right hundred readers matter more than the next hundred thousand.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Why breakneck speed is the right setting.</strong> The case for moving fast is
          not impatience; it is arithmetic. The institutions this work is meant to inform are
          being designed in board rooms and finance ministries this year, on horizons of
          centuries. Their founding instruments are being written now, and amendments after the
          fact are rare. Every quarter the evidence is not in front of the architects is a
          quarter of trusts chartered without it — and a trust chartered wrong stays wrong for a
          very long time. The cost of slowness here is not delay; it is opportunity foregone,
          permanently, at the scale of centuries. There is a second clock running too: the window
          in which an AI-operated public-interest institution can be a thoughtful early example,
          rather than a latecomer to a template someone else set, is roughly eighteen to
          twenty-four months wide. Both clocks argue for the same thing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Speed is affordable here precisely because the work is exploratory rather than
          load-bearing infrastructure that must never break. Everything the Institute builds is
          versioned and reversible; a wrong turn is backed out in minutes, not quarters. When the
          downside of a misstep is a quick correction and the downside of hesitation is a charter
          written without the evidence, the disciplined move is to go fast and fix forward. Fast
          does not mean careless — the editorial passes still happen, the citations still trace to
          the floor, the work still has to survive expert scrutiny. It means removing the
          artificial friction — the permission-seeking, the perfect-before-shipping, the waiting
          for a tidier moment — that adds delay without adding quality. The AI staff is what makes
          this velocity possible at a small institution's budget: the production that would take a
          fifteen-person research shop a year happens in compressed cycles, around the clock, for
          the cost of tokens.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>How we will know it is working.</strong> Velocity without a scoreboard is just
          motion. The Institute will judge its first eighteen months against concrete signals: the
          number of named architects who engage with the Library or a briefing; briefings that
          demonstrably changed a design choice or charter clause; fellows seated from live trust
          proposals; citations of the record in others' work and the press; and a year-two donor
          pipeline real enough to fund the next stage. The first-year audit reports those numbers —
          the wins and the misses — because an institution making the case for fiduciary
          transparency owes its own readers the same.
        </p>

